<paragraph blockId="36.[295,612,1044,1103]" box="[359,549,1044,1070]" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">Turiasauria indet.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="36.[295,612,1044,1103]" box="[295,612,1076,1103]" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">
(
<figureCitation box="[304,382,1076,1102]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="35.[132,143,1895,1912]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1878]" captionTargetId="figure-23@35.[698,1267,768,1324]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIG. 24. — Sauropod teeth from Angeac-Charente: A-D, posterior left maxillary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG11-837) in labial (A), mesial (B), lingual (C) and distal (D) views; E-H, left maxillary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG15-R905) in labial (E), mesial (F), lingual (G) and distal (H) views; I-L, left maxillary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG13-2330) in labial (I), mesial (J), lingual (K) and distal (L) views; M-P, left premaxillary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG14-R289) in labial (M), mesial (N), lingual (O) and distal (P) views; Q-T, dentary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG14-3495) in labial (Q), mesial (R), lingual (S) and distal (T) views; U-X, left dentary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG14- R435) in labial (U), mesial (V), lingual (W) and distal (X) views; Y-AA, maxillary tooth of Macronaria indet. (ANG R-1732) in labial (Y), distal (Z) and lingual (AA) views. Scale bar: A-X, 2 cm; Y-AA, 1 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902095" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902095/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">Figs 24</figureCitation>
A-X; 25B, C; 26; 27)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="36.[130,776,1141,2028]" box="[132,272,1141,1167]" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="36.[130,776,1141,2028]" lastBlockId="36.[810,1458,885,2028]" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">
Sauropod remains are especially abundant in the Early Cretaceous of Angeac-Charente. The locality has yielded many teeth (N = 146), bones (N = 784), and track casts of this group of dinosaurs (
<bibRefCitation author="NERAUDEAU D. &amp; ALLAIN R. &amp; BALLEVRE M. &amp; BATTEN D. J. &amp; TAUT E. &amp; COLIN J. P. &amp; DABARD M. P. &amp; GOMEZ V. &amp; EL ALBANI A. &amp; GOMEZ B. &amp; GROSHENY D. &amp; LE LoeUFF J. &amp; LEPRINCE A. &amp; CLOSAS C. &amp; MASURE E. &amp; MAZIN J. - M. &amp; PHILIPPE M. &amp; POUECH J. &amp; TONG H. &amp; TOURNEPICHE J. - F. &amp; VULLO R." box="[277,513,1267,1294]" pageId="36" pageNumber="717" pagination="1 - 14" refId="ref44595" refString="NERAUDEAU D., ALLAIN R., BALLEVRE M., BATTEN D. J., BUFFE- TAUT E., COLIN J. P., DABARD M. P., DAVIERO- GOMEZ V., EL ALBANI A., GOMEZ B., GROSHENY D., LE LoeUFF J., LEPRINCE A., MARTIN- CLOSAS C., MASURE E., MAZIN J. - M., PHILIPPE M., POUECH J., TONG H., TOURNEPICHE J. - F. &amp; VULLO R. 2012. - The Hauterivian-Barremian lignitic bone bed of Angeac (Charente, SW France): stratigraphical, palaeobiological and palaeogeographical implications. Cretaceous Research 37: 1 - 14. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. cretres. 2012.01.006" type="journal article" year="2012">
Néraudeau 
<emphasis box="[401,452,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">et al.</emphasis>
2012
</bibRefCitation>
; Rozada 
<emphasis box="[610,661,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">et al.</emphasis>
2021). All parts of the skeleton are represented including the braincase, some skull bones, teeth, cervical, dorsal and caudal vertebrae, chevrons, pelvic girdle and all the limb bones (
<figureCitation box="[643,759,1363,1390]" captionStart-0="FIG" captionStart-1="FIG" captionStart-2="FIG" captionStart-3="FIG" captionStartId-0="35.[132,143,1895,1912]" captionStartId-1="36.[132,143,787,804]" captionStartId-2="38.[132,143,1940,1957]" captionStartId-3="39.[132,143,1986,2003]" captionTargetBox-0="[132,1455,215,1878]" captionTargetBox-1="[132,1455,214,744]" captionTargetBox-2="[132,1455,215,1878]" captionTargetBox-3="[239,1347,215,1878]" captionTargetId-0="figure-23@35.[698,1267,768,1324]" captionTargetId-1="figure-724@36.[698,1267,213,745]" captionTargetId-2="figure-29@38.[698,1267,768,1324]" captionTargetId-3="figure-14@39.[239,1347,215,1878]" captionTargetPageId-0="35" captionTargetPageId-1="36" captionTargetPageId-2="38" captionTargetPageId-3="39" captionText-0="FIG. 24. — Sauropod teeth from Angeac-Charente: A-D, posterior left maxillary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG11-837) in labial (A), mesial (B), lingual (C) and distal (D) views; E-H, left maxillary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG15-R905) in labial (E), mesial (F), lingual (G) and distal (H) views; I-L, left maxillary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG13-2330) in labial (I), mesial (J), lingual (K) and distal (L) views; M-P, left premaxillary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG14-R289) in labial (M), mesial (N), lingual (O) and distal (P) views; Q-T, dentary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG14-3495) in labial (Q), mesial (R), lingual (S) and distal (T) views; U-X, left dentary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG14- R435) in labial (U), mesial (V), lingual (W) and distal (X) views; Y-AA, maxillary tooth of Macronaria indet. (ANG R-1732) in labial (Y), distal (Z) and lingual (AA) views. Scale bar: A-X, 2 cm; Y-AA, 1 cm." captionText-1="FIG. 25. — Sauropod embryonic or hatchling teeth from Angeac-Charente: A, tooth of Macronaria indet. (ANGM-18) in lingual view; B, C, tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANGM-118) in labial (B) and lingual (C) views. Scale bar: 500 µm." captionText-2="FIG. 26. — Sauropod caudal vertebrae from Angeac-Charente: A-C, anterior caudal vertebra of Turiasauria indet. (ANG15-R679) in left lateral (A), posterior (B) and dorsal (C) views; D-F, anterior caudal vertebra of Turiasauria indet. (ANG15-R698) in right lateral (D), posterior (E) and dorsal (F) views; G-I, anterior caudal vertebra of Turiasauria indet. (ANG15-R921) in right lateral (G), posterior (H) and dorsal (I) views; J-L, middle caudal vertebra of Turiasauria indet. (ANG15-R652) in right lateral (J), posterior (K) and dorsal (L) views. Scale bar: 10 cm." captionText-3="FIG. 27. — Femur of Turiasauria indet. (ANG19-7000) from the Berriasian of Angeac-Charente discovered during the 2019 campaign. The length of the femur is 2 m. © L. Bocat." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902095" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902097" figureDoi-2="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902099" figureDoi-3="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902101" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/6902095/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/6902097/files/figure.png" httpUri-2="https://zenodo.org/record/6902099/files/figure.png" httpUri-3="https://zenodo.org/record/6902101/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">Figs 24-27</figureCitation>
). Based on the number of femurs and their size, as well as the teeth, there are at least seven different individuals preserved in the site. With the exception of two teeth (see below), all this material belongs to a single taxon. All remaining teeth are reminiscent of the Turiasauria clade (
<bibRefCitation author="ALLAIN R. &amp; ROZADA L. &amp; VULLO R." box="[515,692,1523,1549]" pageId="36" pageNumber="717" refId="ref35270" refString="ALLAIN R., ROZADA L. &amp; VULLO R. 2013. - A cross-perspective into the Early Cretaceous dinosaur faunas from Europe and Asia: new data on the dinosaurs from the Savannakhet Bassin (Laos) and from the lignitic bonebed of Angeac-Charente (France), in VIth International Symposium about Dinosaurs Palaeontology and their Environment, Salas de los Infantes, Spain." type="proceedings" year="2013">
Allain 
<emphasis box="[584,632,1523,1549]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">et al.</emphasis>
2013
</bibRefCitation>
, 2017). We can classify them based on a small number of diagnostic characters.Teeth are heart-shaped in labial and lingual views, with an asymmetric shape induced by a concave distal margin towards the apex (Royo-Torres 
<emphasis box="[466,517,1650,1676]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">et al.</emphasis>
2006, 2017; Royo-Torres &amp; Upchurch 2012; 
<bibRefCitation author="MOCHO P. &amp; TORRES R. &amp; ORTEGA F. &amp; MALAFAIA E. &amp; ESCASO F. &amp; SILVA B." box="[384,583,1682,1708]" pageId="36" pageNumber="717" pagination="861 - 880" refId="ref44477" refString="MOCHO P., ROYO- TORRES R., ORTEGA F., MALAFAIA E., ESCASO F. &amp; SILVA B. 2016. - Turiasauria-like teeth from the Upper Jurassic of the Lusitanian Basin, Portugal. Historical Biology 28 (7): 861 - 880. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 08912963.2015.1049948" type="journal article" year="2016">
Mocho 
<emphasis box="[469,521,1682,1708]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">et al.</emphasis>
2016
</bibRefCitation>
). This feature has been observed in most of the sauropod teeth that have been collected from Angeac-Charente (
<figureCitation box="[492,568,1746,1772]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="35.[132,143,1895,1912]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1878]" captionTargetId="figure-23@35.[698,1267,768,1324]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIG. 24. — Sauropod teeth from Angeac-Charente: A-D, posterior left maxillary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG11-837) in labial (A), mesial (B), lingual (C) and distal (D) views; E-H, left maxillary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG15-R905) in labial (E), mesial (F), lingual (G) and distal (H) views; I-L, left maxillary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG13-2330) in labial (I), mesial (J), lingual (K) and distal (L) views; M-P, left premaxillary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG14-R289) in labial (M), mesial (N), lingual (O) and distal (P) views; Q-T, dentary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG14-3495) in labial (Q), mesial (R), lingual (S) and distal (T) views; U-X, left dentary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG14- R435) in labial (U), mesial (V), lingual (W) and distal (X) views; Y-AA, maxillary tooth of Macronaria indet. (ANG R-1732) in labial (Y), distal (Z) and lingual (AA) views. Scale bar: A-X, 2 cm; Y-AA, 1 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902095" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902095/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">Figs 24</figureCitation>
; 
<figureCitation box="[580,659,1746,1773]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="36.[132,143,787,804]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,214,744]" captionTargetId="figure-724@36.[698,1267,213,745]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIG. 25. — Sauropod embryonic or hatchling teeth from Angeac-Charente: A, tooth of Macronaria indet. (ANGM-18) in lingual view; B, C, tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANGM-118) in labial (B) and lingual (C) views. Scale bar: 500 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902097" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902097/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">25B, C</figureCitation>
). A second character permits referral of these teeth to Turiasauria. When the root is well preserved, several long longitudinal grooves are visible in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Royo-Torres, Cobos &amp; Alcalá" authorityYear="2006" box="[284,407,1842,1867]" class="Reptilia" genus="Turiasaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="36" pageNumber="717" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[284,407,1842,1867]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">Turiasaurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Royo-Torres et al. 2021)" baseAuthorityName="Royo-Torres" baseAuthorityYear="2021" class="Reptilia" genus="Losillasaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="36" pageNumber="717" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[424,559,1841,1867]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">Losillasaurus</emphasis>
(Royo-Torres 
<emphasis box="[721,775,1841,1867]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">et al.</emphasis>
2021)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Britt, Scheetz, Whiting &amp; Wilhite" authorityYear="2017" box="[250,387,1873,1899]" class="Reptilia" genus="Moabosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="36" pageNumber="717" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[250,387,1873,1899]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">Moabosaurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="BRITT B. B. &amp; SCHEETZ R. D. &amp; WHITING M. F. &amp; WILHITE D. R." box="[402,572,1873,1900]" pageId="36" pageNumber="717" pagination="189 - 243" refId="ref36638" refString="BRITT B. B., SCHEETZ R. D., WHITING M. F. &amp; WILHITE D. R. 2017. - Moabosaurus utahensis, n gen., sp., a new sauropod from the Early Cretaceous (Aptian) of North America. Contributions from the Museum of Paleontology, University of Michigan 32: 189 - 243. http: // hdl. handle. net / 2027.42 / 136227" type="journal article" year="2017">
Britt 
<emphasis box="[459,510,1873,1899]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">et al.</emphasis>
2017
</bibRefCitation>
and RRT personal observation). These grooves are also present in the Angeac-Charente taxon (
<figureCitation box="[348,424,1937,1963]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="35.[132,143,1895,1912]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1878]" captionTargetId="figure-23@35.[698,1267,768,1324]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIG. 24. — Sauropod teeth from Angeac-Charente: A-D, posterior left maxillary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG11-837) in labial (A), mesial (B), lingual (C) and distal (D) views; E-H, left maxillary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG15-R905) in labial (E), mesial (F), lingual (G) and distal (H) views; I-L, left maxillary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG13-2330) in labial (I), mesial (J), lingual (K) and distal (L) views; M-P, left premaxillary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG14-R289) in labial (M), mesial (N), lingual (O) and distal (P) views; Q-T, dentary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG14-3495) in labial (Q), mesial (R), lingual (S) and distal (T) views; U-X, left dentary tooth of Turiasauria indet. (ANG14- R435) in labial (U), mesial (V), lingual (W) and distal (X) views; Y-AA, maxillary tooth of Macronaria indet. (ANG R-1732) in labial (Y), distal (Z) and lingual (AA) views. Scale bar: A-X, 2 cm; Y-AA, 1 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902095" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902095/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">Fig. 24</figureCitation>
I-P, U-X) and may be diagnostic for Turiasauria (Royo-Torres 
<emphasis box="[437,487,1969,1995]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">et al.</emphasis>
2021). Moreover, the teeth of Angeac-Charente show a range of crown morphotypes and this variability of forms has also been described in turiasaur teeth from 
<collectingCountry box="[933,1024,917,943]" name="Portugal" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">Portugal</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="MOCHO P. &amp; TORRES R. &amp; ORTEGA F. &amp; MALAFAIA E. &amp; ESCASO F. &amp; SILVA B." box="[1039,1237,917,943]" pageId="36" pageNumber="717" pagination="861 - 880" refId="ref44477" refString="MOCHO P., ROYO- TORRES R., ORTEGA F., MALAFAIA E., ESCASO F. &amp; SILVA B. 2016. - Turiasauria-like teeth from the Upper Jurassic of the Lusitanian Basin, Portugal. Historical Biology 28 (7): 861 - 880. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 08912963.2015.1049948" type="journal article" year="2016">
Mocho 
<emphasis box="[1123,1175,917,943]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">et al.</emphasis>
2016
</bibRefCitation>
) and in 
<taxonomicName authority="(Royo-Torres et al. 2017)" baseAuthorityName="Royo-Torres" baseAuthorityYear="2017" class="Reptilia" genus="Mierasaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="36" pageNumber="717" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1327,1454,918,943]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">Mierasaurus</emphasis>
(Royo-Torres 
<emphasis box="[958,1007,949,975]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">et al.</emphasis>
2017)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Royo-Torres et al. 2021)" baseAuthorityName="Royo-Torres" baseAuthorityYear="2021" class="Reptilia" genus="Losillasaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="36" pageNumber="717" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1126,1257,949,975]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">Losillasaurus</emphasis>
(Royo-Torres 
<emphasis box="[1407,1456,949,975]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">et al.</emphasis>
2021)
</taxonomicName>
. Teeth, in private collections, identical in every way to those of Angeac-Charente, are also present in the Berriasian of Cherves-de-Cognac (RA, TL pers. obs.).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="36.[810,1458,885,2028]" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">
The caudal vertebrae are also useful in determining the systematic position of the Angeac-Charente sauropod (
<figureCitation box="[1318,1392,1108,1134]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="38.[132,143,1940,1957]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1878]" captionTargetId="figure-29@38.[698,1267,768,1324]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIG. 26. — Sauropod caudal vertebrae from Angeac-Charente: A-C, anterior caudal vertebra of Turiasauria indet. (ANG15-R679) in left lateral (A), posterior (B) and dorsal (C) views; D-F, anterior caudal vertebra of Turiasauria indet. (ANG15-R698) in right lateral (D), posterior (E) and dorsal (F) views; G-I, anterior caudal vertebra of Turiasauria indet. (ANG15-R921) in right lateral (G), posterior (H) and dorsal (I) views; J-L, middle caudal vertebra of Turiasauria indet. (ANG15-R652) in right lateral (J), posterior (K) and dorsal (L) views. Scale bar: 10 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902099" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902099/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
). The anterior caudal vertebrae are procoelous with a slightly convex posterior articulation (
<figureCitation box="[1045,1118,1172,1198]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="38.[132,143,1940,1957]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1878]" captionTargetId="figure-29@38.[698,1267,768,1324]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIG. 26. — Sauropod caudal vertebrae from Angeac-Charente: A-C, anterior caudal vertebra of Turiasauria indet. (ANG15-R679) in left lateral (A), posterior (B) and dorsal (C) views; D-F, anterior caudal vertebra of Turiasauria indet. (ANG15-R698) in right lateral (D), posterior (E) and dorsal (F) views; G-I, anterior caudal vertebra of Turiasauria indet. (ANG15-R921) in right lateral (G), posterior (H) and dorsal (I) views; J-L, middle caudal vertebra of Turiasauria indet. (ANG15-R652) in right lateral (J), posterior (K) and dorsal (L) views. Scale bar: 10 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902099" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902099/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
A-I) whereas the middle become amphicoelous or amphyplatyan (
<figureCitation box="[1152,1224,1204,1230]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="38.[132,143,1940,1957]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1878]" captionTargetId="figure-29@38.[698,1267,768,1324]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIG. 26. — Sauropod caudal vertebrae from Angeac-Charente: A-C, anterior caudal vertebra of Turiasauria indet. (ANG15-R679) in left lateral (A), posterior (B) and dorsal (C) views; D-F, anterior caudal vertebra of Turiasauria indet. (ANG15-R698) in right lateral (D), posterior (E) and dorsal (F) views; G-I, anterior caudal vertebra of Turiasauria indet. (ANG15-R921) in right lateral (G), posterior (H) and dorsal (I) views; J-L, middle caudal vertebra of Turiasauria indet. (ANG15-R652) in right lateral (J), posterior (K) and dorsal (L) views. Scale bar: 10 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902099" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902099/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
J-L). The presence of a convex posterior articulation on sauropod caudal vertebrae was acquired several times during sauropod evolution (Wilson 2002; Upchurch 
<emphasis box="[920,966,1299,1325]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">et al.</emphasis>
2004; 
<bibRefCitation author="D'EMIC M. D." box="[1032,1170,1299,1326]" pageId="36" pageNumber="717" pagination="624 - 671" refId="ref38529" refString="D'EMIC M. D. 2012. - The early evolution of titanosauriform sauropod dinosaurs. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society 166: 624 - 671. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.2012.00853. x" type="journal article" year="2012">D’Emic 2012</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="MANNION P. D. &amp; ALLAIN R. &amp; MOINE O." box="[1181,1383,1299,1326]" pageId="36" pageNumber="717" pagination="3217" refId="ref42869" refString="MANNION P. D., ALLAIN R. &amp; MOINE O. 2017. - The earliest known titanosauriform sauropod dinosaur and the evolution of Brachiosauridae. PeerJ 5: e 3217. https: // doi. org / 10.7717 / peerj. 3217" type="journal article" year="2017">
Mannion 
<emphasis box="[1281,1327,1299,1325]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">et al.</emphasis>
2017
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="MANNION P. D. &amp; UPCHURCH P. &amp; SCHWARZ D. &amp; WINGS O." box="[1393,1446,1300,1326]" pageId="36" pageNumber="717" pagination="784 - 909" refId="ref42915" refString="MANNION P. D., UPCHURCH P., SCHWARZ D. &amp; WINGS O. 2019. - Taxonomic affinities of the putative titanosaurs from the Late Jurassic Tendaguru Formation of Tanzania: phylogenetic and biogeographic implications for eusauropod dinosaur evolution. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 185: 784 - 909. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / zoolinnean / zly 068" type="journal article" year="2019">2019</bibRefCitation>
) and can be seen in diplodocids, titanosaurs and mamenchisaurids. The procoelous condition was also acquired in Turiasauria, as described for the Late Jurassic 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Royo-Torres, Cobos &amp; Alcalá" authorityYear="2006" box="[1158,1276,1396,1421]" class="Reptilia" genus="Turiasaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="36" pageNumber="717" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1158,1276,1396,1421]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">Turiasaurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1329,1456,1395,1421]" class="Reptilia" genus="Losillasaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="36" pageNumber="717" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1329,1456,1395,1421]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">Losillasaurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="CASANOVAS M. L. &amp; SANTAFE J. V. &amp; SANZ J. L." box="[821,1046,1427,1453]" pageId="36" pageNumber="717" pagination="99 - 122" refId="ref37646" refString="CASANOVAS M. L., SANTAFE J. V. &amp; SANZ J. L. 2001. - Losillasaurus giganteus, un nuevo sauropodo del transito Jurasico-Cretacico de la cuenca de &quot; Los Serranos &quot; (Valencia, Espana). Paleontologia i Evolucio 32 - 33: 99 - 122." type="journal article" year="2001">
Casanovas 
<emphasis box="[936,986,1427,1453]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">et al.</emphasis>
2001
</bibRefCitation>
; Royo-Torres 
<emphasis box="[1196,1246,1427,1453]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">et al.</emphasis>
2006, 2021). It has also been reported in the posterior series of Early Cretaceous 
<taxonomicName box="[814,938,1492,1517]" class="Reptilia" genus="Mierasaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="36" pageNumber="717" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[814,938,1492,1517]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">Mierasaurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Britt, Scheetz, Whiting &amp; Wilhite" authorityYear="2017" box="[993,1126,1491,1517]" class="Reptilia" genus="Moabosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="36" pageNumber="717" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[993,1126,1491,1517]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">Moabosaurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Royo-Torres 
<emphasis box="[1278,1330,1491,1517]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">et al.</emphasis>
2017; 
<bibRefCitation author="BRITT B. B. &amp; SCHEETZ R. D. &amp; WHITING M. F. &amp; WILHITE D. R." pageId="36" pageNumber="717" pagination="189 - 243" refId="ref36638" refString="BRITT B. B., SCHEETZ R. D., WHITING M. F. &amp; WILHITE D. R. 2017. - Moabosaurus utahensis, n gen., sp., a new sauropod from the Early Cretaceous (Aptian) of North America. Contributions from the Museum of Paleontology, University of Michigan 32: 189 - 243. http: // hdl. handle. net / 2027.42 / 136227" type="journal article" year="2017">
Britt 
<emphasis box="[813,861,1523,1549]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">et al.</emphasis>
2017
</bibRefCitation>
). This feature is considered to be synapomorphic for Turiasauria in some phylogenetic analyses (
<bibRefCitation author="CARBALLIDO J. L. &amp; SANDER P. M." pageId="36" pageNumber="717" pagination="335 - 387" refId="ref37360" refString="CARBALLIDO J. L. &amp; SANDER P. M. 2014. - Postcranial axial skeleton of Europasaurus holgeri (Dinosauria, Sauropoda) from the Upper Jurassic of Germany: implications for sauropod ontogeny and phylogenetic relationships of basal Macronaria. Journal of Systematic Palaeontology 12 (3): 335 - 387. https: // doi. org / 10.108 0 / 14772019.2013.764935" type="journal article" year="2014">Carballido &amp; Sander 2014</bibRefCitation>
). The neural arch of anterior caudal vertebrae is restricted to the anterior half of the centrum. This character is shared with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Royo-Torres, Cobos &amp; Alcalá" authorityYear="2006" box="[811,927,1651,1676]" class="Reptilia" genus="Turiasaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="36" pageNumber="717" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[811,927,1651,1676]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">Turiasaurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[939,1062,1650,1676]" class="Reptilia" genus="Losillasaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="36" pageNumber="717" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[939,1062,1650,1676]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">Losillasaurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Britt, Scheetz, Whiting &amp; Wilhite" authorityYear="2017" box="[1073,1202,1650,1676]" class="Reptilia" genus="Moabosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="36" pageNumber="717" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1073,1202,1650,1676]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">Moabosaurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority=", Cetiosaurus" authorityName="Cetiosaurus" box="[1213,1455,1651,1677]" class="Reptilia" genus="Mierasaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="36" pageNumber="717" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1213,1333,1651,1676]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">Mierasaurus</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[1343,1455,1651,1677]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">Cetiosaurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the Titanosauriformes(Upchurch 
<emphasis box="[1196,1243,1682,1708]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">et al.</emphasis>
2004; 
<bibRefCitation author="D'EMIC M. D." box="[1310,1448,1682,1708]" pageId="36" pageNumber="717" pagination="624 - 671" refId="ref38529" refString="D'EMIC M. D. 2012. - The early evolution of titanosauriform sauropod dinosaurs. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society 166: 624 - 671. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.2012.00853. x" type="journal article" year="2012">D’Emic 2012</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="BRITT B. B. &amp; SCHEETZ R. D. &amp; WHITING M. F. &amp; WILHITE D. R." box="[813,976,1714,1740]" pageId="36" pageNumber="717" pagination="189 - 243" refId="ref36638" refString="BRITT B. B., SCHEETZ R. D., WHITING M. F. &amp; WILHITE D. R. 2017. - Moabosaurus utahensis, n gen., sp., a new sauropod from the Early Cretaceous (Aptian) of North America. Contributions from the Museum of Paleontology, University of Michigan 32: 189 - 243. http: // hdl. handle. net / 2027.42 / 136227" type="journal article" year="2017">
Britt 
<emphasis box="[867,916,1714,1740]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">et al.</emphasis>
2017
</bibRefCitation>
; Royo-Torres 
<emphasis box="[1123,1173,1714,1740]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">et al.</emphasis>
2017). The presence in the Angeac-Charente taxon of caudal vertebrae with short lateral processes (‘caudal ribs’) that do not extend beyond the posterior end of the centrum suggests affinities with Titanosauriformes (
<bibRefCitation author="MANNION P. D. &amp; UPCHURCH P. &amp; SCHWARZ D. &amp; WINGS O." box="[821,1034,1841,1868]" pageId="36" pageNumber="717" pagination="784 - 909" refId="ref42915" refString="MANNION P. D., UPCHURCH P., SCHWARZ D. &amp; WINGS O. 2019. - Taxonomic affinities of the putative titanosaurs from the Late Jurassic Tendaguru Formation of Tanzania: phylogenetic and biogeographic implications for eusauropod dinosaur evolution. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 185: 784 - 909. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / zoolinnean / zly 068" type="journal article" year="2019">
Mannion 
<emphasis box="[925,975,1841,1867]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">et al.</emphasis>
2019
</bibRefCitation>
; Royo-Torres 
<emphasis box="[1181,1230,1841,1867]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">et al.</emphasis>
2021).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="36.[810,1458,885,2028]" pageId="36" pageNumber="717">
Two additional possible synapomorphic characters for Turiasauria seen in specimens from Angeac-Charente include slightly opisthocoelous posterior dorsal centra, as well as a high neural arch below the postzygapophyses of the posterior dorsal vertebrae (
<bibRefCitation author="CARBALLIDO J. L. &amp; SANDER P. M." box="[998,1286,2001,2027]" pageId="36" pageNumber="717" pagination="335 - 387" refId="ref37360" refString="CARBALLIDO J. L. &amp; SANDER P. M. 2014. - Postcranial axial skeleton of Europasaurus holgeri (Dinosauria, Sauropoda) from the Upper Jurassic of Germany: implications for sauropod ontogeny and phylogenetic relationships of basal Macronaria. Journal of Systematic Palaeontology 12 (3): 335 - 387. https: // doi. org / 10.108 0 / 14772019.2013.764935" type="journal article" year="2014">Carballido &amp; Sander 2014</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
